<DOC><DOCNO>WSJ900716-0052</DOCNO><DOCID>900716-0052.</DOCID><HL>   Italy Urges the EC   To Discuss Energy   With U.S. and Japan</HL><DATE>07/16/90</DATE><SO>WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), PAGE A5A</SO><CO>   EUROP JAPAN</CO><IN>ENVIRONMENT (ENV)</IN><LP>   BRUSSELS -- Italy asked the European Community Friday tolaunch a broad debate with the U.S. and Japan on globalenergy issues, including a discussion on imposing taxes onenergy consumption.   In a report, the Italian government said the &quot;rapidgrowth&quot; in global energy use demands a concertedinternational effort to cut consumption, save energy andpromote renewable sources of it.</LP><TEXT>   &quot;All these actions . . . need to be international with themore industrialized countries taking the lead so as toprevent serious consequences for the world economy,&quot; thereport said.   The report assesses global energy output and consumptiontrends. It will be discussed at a meeting in Rome today byministers responsible for energy matters of the 12 ECnations.   The energy document said the EC's energy goals until 1995,drafted in 1985, are outdated because oil prices have droppedsharply since then, and the 1986 accident at Chernobylshattered confidence in nuclear power.   &quot;However, the most important reason for rethinking allenergy matters is the concern over the environment that hasarisen in recent years and specifically the fear of a globalwarming of our planet due to the action of greenhouse gases,&quot;the report said.</TEXT></DOC>